a. Learn how to apply inline CSS to style individual HTML elements.
b. Learn how to use internal CSS for styling multiple elements within a single HTML page.
c. Learn how to use external CSS to maintain a separate stylesheet for consistent styling across web pages.

So, hereâ€™s a complete example that covers all three types of CSS â€” inline, internal, and external.

ðŸ§© 1. HTML File â€“ index.html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Applying CSS Styling</title>

    <!-- Internal CSS -->
    <style>
        body {
            background-color: #f2f2f2;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }

        h1 {
            color: darkblue;
            text-align: center;
            text-decoration: underline;
        }

        p {
            color: #333333;
            font-size: 18px;
        }

        .highlight {
            color: green;
            font-weight: bold;
        }

        .box {
            border: 2px solid black;
            padding: 15px;
            background-color: white;
            width: 50%;
            margin: auto;
            border-radius: 10px;
        }
    </style>

    <!-- External CSS Link -->
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
    <!-- Inline CSS -->
    <h1 style="color: red;">Applying CSS Styling to Web Pages</h1>

    <div class="box">
        <p>This paragraph is styled using <b>internal CSS</b>.</p>
        <p class="highlight">This one uses a class with internal CSS styling.</p>
        <p style="color: blue; font-style: italic;">This line uses <b>inline CSS</b> directly inside the tag.</p>
    </div>

    <p class="footer-text">This paragraph is styled using <b>external CSS</b>.</p>
</body>
</html>

ðŸŽ¨ 2. External CSS File â€“ style.css
.footer-text {
    text-align: center;
    color: purple;
    font-size: 20px;
    background-color: #e0e0e0;
    padding: 10px;
    border-radius: 5px;
}
